        <h2 class="bw-modular__title" style="font-size:clamp(24px, 3vw, 34px);">Choose the kitchen format that matches the room, not only the inspiration image</h2>
        <p class="bw-modular__copy">Every kitchen layout has a different relationship with circulation, storage intensity, and visual openness. Shortlist the one that best matches the way the home functions.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="bw-modular__cards">
        <article class="bw-modular__card"><h3>L-shape</h3><p>Ideal when the kitchen needs to feel open, balanced, and efficient without becoming visually dense. A strong fit for many apartments and family homes.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-modular__card"><h3>U-shape</h3><p>Best when storage demand is high, countertop continuity matters, and the room is wide enough to support a comfortable central aisle.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-modular__card"><h3>Parallel</h3><p>Excellent for tighter footprints where two facing runs can split washing, prep, cooking, and pantry functions more efficiently than a single-wall solution.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-modular__card"><h3>Straight</h3><p>Strong for compact homes that need one disciplined linear run with careful vertical planning and a cleaner visual profile.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-modular__card"><h3>Island</h3><p>Works best in larger open homes where the kitchen is also a hosting and gathering zone, not only a service area.</p></article>
        <article class="bw-modular__card"><h3>Still choosing?</h3><p>Start with the room dimensions, your cooking pattern, appliance list, and how open or enclosed you want the kitchen to feel. The right layout usually reveals itself from there.</p></article>
